<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="description" content="Digital Engagement" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>TCSW Digital Engagement Strategy</title></head><body><div><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><thead><tr style="height:28.1pt"><th style="border-bottom-color:#262626; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; padding-bottom:5.65pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:481.95pt"><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 1.7pt; orphans:0; text-align:right; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></th></tr></thead></table><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">The College of Social Work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The College of Social Work (TCSW) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is the centre of excellence for social work and provides resources to its members to uphold and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">strengthen standards of professional practice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It holds the professional standards for social work, supports the professional development of social workers, and campaigns on issues relating to social work policy and practice.  An independent membership org</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">anisation, The College provides quality assurance for initial and post-qualifying education through its training and education endorsement scheme.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Like colleges for other professions, our role is to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hold the standards for the profession and support and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">enable our members to meet those standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Be the voice of the profession to policy makers and the media, ensuring that our members speak up for the profession</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Be led by and accountable to our members – the profession. We do this in order to improve the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">outcomes for the people served by our profession.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Frequency, scope and impact of consultations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">TCSW notes that a number of recent Ofsted consultations have been published with a very limited time period in which to respond. We would ask that, if possible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, this does not occur in the future in order that we can all continue to work together constructively.  As an organisation with a duty and responsibility to consult our membership, Professional Assembly and Children and Families Faculty, it does pose diffi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">culties for TCSW when short timescales are offered for consultations.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Ofsted and its decision making and impact</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As has been acknowledged by the ADCS, the LGA and Ofsted itself, the judgments reached including, in particular, the grading can have significant consequences for a local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">authority and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> seriously impact upon morale and, indeed, imperil the very improvements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> required.  There are concerns among a range of stakeholders particularly in a climate of austerity about the role being played by Ofsted in contributing to unhelpful pressures upon local authorities seeking to deliver excellent services. TCSW would sugges</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t  that some form of independent advisory group composed of key stakeholders, including members of the TCSW, should work with Ofsted to explore how quality is defined and to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  support  the development of risk management</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (as recommended by the Munro Review) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cultures and learning organisations. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">TCSW believes that the voice of social work should be at the core of the inspection and a mechanism in place which would help with the analysis of work place culture, allowing management to identify early on any press</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ure points that are impacting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> good practice. TCSW would argue that the Principal Children and Family Social Worker (PSW), a key recommendation of the Munro Review, offers a means of linking frontline issues to strategic management. We have established a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> PSW network in conjunction with the Department for Education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">owever</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> we are concerned that the rate of adoption greatly contrasts among different local authorities. We would like to see incorporated within the inspection framework an indication of wheth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">er an authority has a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">PSW in place. TCSW will do the utmost to ensure that these PSW’s are supported and linked to other PSWs across England.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Practice Improvement Role</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">TCSW notes the proposed addition of the practice improvement role to the Ofsted remit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and have welcomed our involvement in early discussions. G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iven that this greatly strengthens</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the position of Ofsted with respect to the definition of a quality social work service to children and families, we consider it even more essential that an indepen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dent advisory group (as referred to above)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is involved in discussions about the parameters of the role and in a consult</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ative capacity with respect to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the judgements mad</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e about how to improve quality.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> TCSW has been working with one local authority to develo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">p an action plan to support the professional development and supervision of social workers by mapping training needs to the Professional Capabilities Framework. While still in its early stages, TCSW expects to expand this role further in the future </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> aut</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">horities where Ofsted have made recommendations for improvements.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Employee standards</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The pressure of high caseload volumes is very often cited by social workers as a form</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">idable barrier to good practice, although</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> defining what constitutes a ‘hig</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h’ number </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is difficult</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. A single case could involve intensive work over a period of many months, while another might feasibly be ‘closed’ within a matter of days. As such, TCSW would like to see a focus on how social work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cases and tasks </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are allocated, supervised, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd evaluated. The Standards for Employers and Supervision Framewor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">k developed by the Social Work T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ask Force must take on greater significance within the inspection framework to ensure that social workers have manageable workloads and receive appropriate su</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pervision. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Multi-agency inspections</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ofsted has announced that multi-agency inspections will begin from April 2015. These inspections were due to begin this year but were postponed due to operational issues. While it is crucial that these issues are iron</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed out, TCSW notes that Scotland has been conducting multi-agency inspections for a number of years</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> already. Given the frequency with which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> significant coordination issues</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are highlighted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in Serious Case Reviews, TCSW would urge that these inspections are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not delayed any further. The evaluation of the Daniel Pelka and Keanu Williams cases contained similarities with regards to multi-agency coordination and information sharing. We would therefore like to better establish what constitutes ‘good’ practice in t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">erms of regular and effective monitoring and evaluation of multi-agency practice. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Monitoring</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the effectiveness of inter-agency and in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ter-professional collaborative </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">practice should be examined </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at all levels of case management and all levels of service deliv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ery, from early help to adoption or reunification from care. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While there is an implicit expectation for social care and early help services to interact, we believe that that the relevant indicator, without being overly-prescriptive, should go further in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">defining what this might practically entail. TCSW consider</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that name</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d social workers should play a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consultative role as members of early help teams around families and a key case management role for all teams around families in which a child</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is assessed as ‘in need’ of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">additional family support, child protection</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">looked after child or transition to adulthood service. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The voice of children and families </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is extremely important that those who use services are at the heart of the inspe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ction process. How is the child’s journey placed at the heart of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">process?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This is mentioned in the descriptors but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">more detail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is required in relation to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Moreover, we consider it vital that that engagement is wit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h families in the widest se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nse.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Children’s own perspectives on who they consider family and who matters to them has been recognised in Family Group Conferences and in evaluations of intensive outreach and child protection services as offering productive possibilities for safety plan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ning and decision making. These evaluations could provide a strong methodology for the inspection process and we would encourage collaboration with researchers when testing the dimensions to be used in deciding on the approaches to improving services to be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> recommended by Ofsted.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Arial Bold'; font-size:16pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><sp